Italian Stocks Rise; Enel Green Power, Generali Luxottica, Tenaris Active

-- B y   F r a n c e s c a   C i n e l l i
-- 
2011-02-24T11:29:42Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-23/brembo-generali-trevi-may-move-italian-equity-market-preview.html
Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index 
reversed earlier losses, gaining 39.87, or 0.2 percent, to
21,969.66 at 12:21 p.m. in Milan, a first gain in five days.  The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.    Assicurazioni Generali SpA  (G IM) lost 1.4 percent to 15.76
euros. Italy’s biggest insurer said yesterday 2010 premiums rose
3.8 percent to 73.2 billion euros. BofA Merrill Lynch Global
Research, which has a “neutral” rating on the stock, said in a
note that the figures were “slightly weak.”    Enel Green Power SpA  (EGPW IM) advanced for a third day,
gaining 2.5 percent to 1.74 euros. Italy’s largest renewable
energy company, which will join the Stoxx Europe 600 Index on
March 21, had its price estimate increased to 1.9 euros from 1.8
euros at Intermonte Sim SpA. The brokerage cited a positive
impact of rising oil prices and reiterated an “outperform”
rating.    Eni SpA  (ENI IM), Italy’s biggest oil company, advanced 2.1
percent to 17.44 euros, snapping a three-day loss, as a gauge
for European oil stocks advanced for the first time this week.  Saipem SpA (SPM IM), Europe’s largest oil-services company,
advanced 1.7 percent to 35.21 euros.    Luxottica Group SpA  (LUX IM) fell 1.1 percent to 21.63
euros. Nomura Holdings Inc. said in a note that “we like the
Luxottica story for its growth potential in emerging markets and
margin opportunity.” The world’s biggest maker of glasses will
report earnings on Feb. 28.    Tenaris SA  (TEN IM) dropped 2.5 percent to 16.58 euros,
extending a 2.4 percent loss yesterday. The world’s largest
maker of seamless pipes said fourth-quarter profit rose 44
percent on higher sales.  Deutsche Bank AG, which has a “buy” rating, said in a
note that while quarterly results were weaker than expected, the
outlook remains positive.    Trevi Finanziaria SpA  (TFI IM) retreated 1.3 percent to
9.82 euros, a fourth straight loss. The provider of excavation
services said it suspended a 1.5 million-euro contract in Libya
and repatriated five employees. Intermonte Sim SpA downgraded
the stock to “neutral” from “buy.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
Francesca Cinelli in Milan at 
 fcinelli@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Merritt at   dmerritt1@bloomberg.net . 